}



At the primary and secondary school levels, the 100 per cent transition of students and the introduction of the competency-based curriculum (CBC) dominated discussion in the year.
That a significant number of secondary schools would be forced to take extra classes to actualise the transition rate without prior notice when statistics of candidates at class eight is known well in advance speaks volumes about planning and governance in the sector.
Junior secondary
Furthermore, the infrastructural requirements in secondary schools in the years 2023 and 2024 and the criteria of admitting students into junior secondary without an examination or any other acceptable objective method are issues of concern.
 The Technical and Vocational Education Training sub sector was possibly the most successful in the sector. More institutes were opened, more than 2,000 lecturers were recruited and a number of lecturers promoted to principals of the new institutes has raised the morale. The recruitment process of lecturers was, however, slow and the procedure tedious and repetitive.
The Covid-19 pandemic worldwide has come with major challenges in the education sector with no precedence to fall back to for solutions. The effect it is having on the calendars at all levels of education is a major challenge that will affect the system for years to come.



