Special curriculum
As we enter 2021, there is an urgent need for all institutions to review their strategic plans since closure has affected implementation timelines. In addition, there are major issues to be considered.
First, all institutions must strategise on how to provide education with all the protocols required to combat the pandemic. Secondly, secondary schools have to plan on how to accommodate double intake in 2023 and 2024 and retain the CBC students for six years.
The TSC would have to plan to provide the teachers required for a diversified and specialised curriculum. The ministry and the Treasury must plan for a longer period of provision of capitation for secondary schools, which cost more per student than at the primary level.  The universities would have to revise their curricula and teaching methods to be in tandem with the CBC requirements.
At the ministry and in the university councils, the expectation of parents that the recruitment of vice-chancellors will be streamlined to a level that the transitions between them be seamless.
Lecturers should be focusing on research and teaching instead of demonstrating against their bosses.
